# RunPod Deployment Configuration
# ============================================
# Copy this file to .env.runpod and fill in your values.
# This file is used by: scripts/deploy-runpod.sh
#
# IMPORTANT: .env.runpod is in .gitignore and should NEVER be committed.
# It contains sensitive credentials and pod IDs.

# ============================================
# REQUIRED - RunPod Deployment Settings
# ============================================

# Your RunPod pod ID
# Get this from the RunPod console after creating your pod
# Example: "abc123xyz"
# See: https://www.runpod.io/console/pods
RUNPOD_POD_ID=your-pod-id-here

# RunPod SSH user (full identifier including session token)
# Get this from your RunPod SSH connection string:
# Run the pod once and SSH into it to find the full user identifier
# The connection string is shown in the RunPod console:
#   ssh <RUNPOD_SSH_USER>@ssh.runpod.io -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
# Example: lvgn83xrikynaw-64411dcb (includes pod-id + session token)
RUNPOD_SSH_USER=your-ssh-user-here

# Docker registry image URL (where to push the built image)
# Format: registry.io/username/imagename
# Examples:
#   - ghcr.io/z0rd0n88/bratbot         (GitHub Container Registry)
#   - docker.io/z0rd0n88/bratbot       (Docker Hub)
#   - your-registry.azurecr.io/bratbot (Azure Container Registry)
REGISTRY_IMAGE=ghcr.io/your-username/bratbot

# Docker image tag (version identifier)
# Default: runpod-latest
# You can change this for different model configurations
# Example: runpod-qwen3-8b, runpod-v1.0, etc.
IMAGE_TAG=runpod-latest

# SSH private key for connecting to the RunPod pod via SSH
# Default: ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 (Ed25519 key)
# Alternative: ~/.ssh/id_rsa (RSA key)
# Make sure the public key is added to the pod's authorized_keys
RUNPOD_SSH_KEY=~/.ssh/id_ed25519
#
# WSL users: your Windows SSH key is mounted at /mnt/c/Users/<Username>/.ssh/
# Set this explicitly if ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 doesn't exist in WSL:
#   RUNPOD_SSH_KEY=/mnt/c/Users/YourWindowsUsername/.ssh/id_ed25519
# The script auto-detects this when RUNPOD_SSH_KEY is unset, but setting it
# explicitly here is more reliable.

# ============================================
# Pod Template Environment Variables Reference
# ============================================
#
# The following variables are NOT read from this file.
# Instead, they are set in the RunPod Pod Template console.
#
# Copy these to your RunPod Pod Template environment variables section:
#
# DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=your-actual-bot-token
#   → Your Discord bot token (get from https://discord.com/developers)
#
# DISCORD_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id
#   → Your Discord application ID
#
# DISCORD_PUBLIC_KEY=your-public-key
#   → Ed25519 public key for signature verification
#
# OLLAMA_BASE_URL=http://localhost:11434
#   → Internal Ollama API URL (localhost since it's in the same pod)
#
# OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen3:8b
#   → Model name to load from Ollama registry
#   → Or use custom GGUF: my-custom-model
#   → See README for model recommendations and costs
#
# LLM_API_URL=http://localhost:8000
#   → Internal FastAPI model server URL (localhost same pod)
#
# REDIS_URL=rediss://default:xxx@xxx.upstash.io:6379
#   → Upstash Redis connection string (external managed service, uses TLS)
#   → Get from: https://console.upstash.com/redis
#
# Optional variables:
# LOG_LEVEL=INFO             → Logging level
# GUILD_ID=123...            → Discord guild ID for dev sync
# LLM_BRAT_LEVEL=3           → Default brattiness (1-3, where 3 is maximum brat)
# RATE_LIMIT_USER_SECONDS=5  → Per-user cooldown
# RATE_LIMIT_CHANNEL_PER_MINUTE=10  → Per-channel rate limit
# OLLAMA_TEMPERATURE=0.9     → Sampling temperature (0.0-1.0)
# OLLAMA_NUM_PREDICT=-1      → Max output tokens (-1 = unlimited)
# OLLAMA_NUM_CTX=32768       → Context window in tokens

# ============================================
# Setup Checklist
# ============================================
#
# Before running ./scripts/deploy-runpod.sh:
#
# 1. [  ] Create a GitHub Container Registry token
#    → https://github.com/settings/tokens?type=beta
#    → Scopes: write:packages, read:packages
#    → Store safely (you'll only see it once)
#
# 2. [  ] Create an Upstash Redis instance
#    → https://console.upstash.com/redis
#    → Copy the rediss:// URL to REDIS_URL
#
# 3. [  ] Create a RunPod Network Volume
#    → https://www.runpod.io/console/user/volumes
#    → Size: 15 GB (for model cache)
#    → Region: Same as your pod
#
# 4. [  ] Upload your GGUF model file (optional)
#    → Spin up temp CPU pod with volume attached
#    → Upload to /workspace/models/your-model.gguf
#    → Update OLLAMA_MODEL in pod template
#
# 5. [  ] Create a RunPod Pod Template
#    → Go to: https://www.runpod.io/console/user/templates
#    → Base image: ghcr.io/your-username/bratbot:runpod-latest
#    → GPU: RTX A4000 or RTX 3070 (see README for recommendations)
#    → Network Volume: Attach at /workspace
#    → Environment variables: See section above
#
# 6. [  ] Deploy and test
#    → ./scripts/deploy-runpod.sh build
#    → ./scripts/deploy-runpod.sh push
#    → Create pod from template in RunPod console
#    → ./scripts/deploy-runpod.sh ssh
#    → supervisorctl status  (check all processes)
